    <title>The Garmin Forerunner 255 Music is nearly half off for Prime Day</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Garmin Forerunner 255S smartwatch on a colorful background" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/GsOZ1ZP9k-vr-ydFndXP8a23PlU=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73640036/IMG_0265.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;You get a bunch of features for a much more palatable price.&lt;/em&gt; | Photo by Victoria Song / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="NWFDSB"&gt;When I first reviewed the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23171721/garmin-forerunner-255s-review-running-watch"&gt;Garmin Forerunner 255&lt;/a&gt;, I said it was a steal for runners who wanted dual-frequency GPS at a more palatable price. Well, thanks to Prime Day discounts, it’s even more palatable at $219.99 — a whopping 45 percent off list price.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="CYopf6"&gt;Dual-frequency GPS makes a big difference for accuracy, but most other watches with it still cost a pretty penny. &lt;a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B09NMLVQ64?tag=theverge02-20" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;Garmin’s Epix watch&lt;/a&gt; is also on sale for $560, but that has more bulk and costs over $300 more. (But it’s also a good deal if you like a bigger watch and OLED displays.) Personally, I like lighter smartwatches for running, and the Forerunner is an excellent option for marathoners on a budget. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="D85mwP"&gt;&lt;div data-anthem-component="productcard:12447607"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p id="DeLNsg"&gt;Technically, there is a newer &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23632332/garmin-forerunner-265s-review-oled-smartwatch-running"&gt;Forerunner 265&lt;/a&gt; model, but the main thing you’re getting...&lt;/p&gt;
